# Performance Optimization

> **Reference**: This guide extends the [UX/UI Design Principles](ux-ui.mdc). Make sure you're familiar with core UX/UI principles before diving into performance optimization specifics.

## üìã Overview

Performance is a critical aspect of user experience. Users expect websites to load quickly and respond instantly. This guide focuses on performance optimization from a UX/UI perspective, emphasizing perceived performance‚Äîhow fast a site *feels* to users, not just technical metrics.

**Why it matters:**
- Slow sites increase abandonment and reduce trust.
- Even small delays can measurably reduce conversion and satisfaction.
- **Perceived performance** often matters as much as actual load time.

## üéØ Core Performance Principles

### 1. Actual vs Perceived Performance
- **Actual**: Technical metrics (load time, Time to Interactive)
- **Perceived**: User's subjective experience of speed
- Focus on what users *feel*, not just what metrics show

### 2. Critical Rendering Path
- Optimize resources that block initial render
- Prioritize above-the-fold content
- Defer non-critical resources

### 3. Progressive Enhancement
- Show content as soon as possible
- Load enhancements progressively
- Ensure basic functionality works immediately

### 4. Performance Budget
- Set limits on resource sizes
- Monitor bundle sizes
- Balance features with performance

